@node "Introduction" "Introduction to BibCard"
BibCard is a database program to control @{"BiBTeX" link "latex" 0} files. These are files with
references to articles, books, conferences etc. and are used in combination
with @{"LaTeX" link "latex" 0}. Read the documentation for LaTex and BiBTeX how to use these
files.

It requires minimal v2.04 (kickstart V37) of the operating system. It has been
written and tested (using Mungwall and Enforcer) under v3.1 (V40), but should
run under v2.04 and higher.

For selecting a screen mode V38 of the asl.library must be present.

BibCard has the following features:

  - It can handle multiple bib files at once. It opens for
    every bib file a new window.

  - It has an extended Annotation option.

  - It has a preamble option

  - It supports string entries.

  - Every entry that is unknown for BibCard will be stored,
    saved and is also editable.

  - For every entry and field is some help, explaining where it is used
    for.

  - It can read "" and {} pair's for field delimiters.

  - Sensitive help.

  - Search option.

  - Supports text entering through the textfield.gadget.

  - BibCard opens on the Workbench, a public screen or it's own public
    screen.

  - For a custom screen any font can be choosen.

  - Is font sensitive.

  - Is an AppWindow.

  - Supports icon creation for saved bibfiles.

  - Iconfy and DropBox.

  - Extra User fields.

  - You name it, I make it...

BibCard supports now the textfield gadget for text entering. The suplied
install script copies the textfield.gadget to SYS:Classes/Gadgets for
kickstart V39 and above. For versions V37 and V38 it should be installed in a
directory Gadgets in the same directory where BibCard is installed.
@endnode

@node "Install" "Installation"
BiBCard can be installed with the supplied installer script. The Installer
command must be somewhere in your path. If you don't have it then you are
working with KS1.3 or below so you can't run this program anyway.

The installer script detects under which version of the operating system you
are working and takes care of the right place for the textfield.gadget,

If you want to install BibCard by hand you must read further.

Install for KS2.04:

    - Copy BibCard (and it's icon) to the desired place.

    - Create a directory Gadgets in the same directory as BibCard.

    - Copy the textfield.gadget to the Gadget directory.

    - Ready!


Install for KS3.0 and above:

    - Copy BibCard (and it's icon) to the desired place.

    - Copy the textfield.gadget to sys:Classes/Gadgets.

    - Ready!
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
BibCard can be started from the @{"Workbench" link "Workbench" 0} or the @{"Shell" link "Shell" 0}. Both methods give you
some options. BibCard uses first its internal configuration, second the
options set in the @{"preferences" link "Prefs" 0} file, and third any options given on the
command line or as a tool type. An option set at the command line, or as tool
type overides any thing set in the preferences file.
@endnode

@node "Shell" "Shell Usage"
 The template is:

    FILE,DEFSCREEN=DEF/S,CUSTSCREEN=SCR/S,PUBSCREEN=PUB/K

Or more readable:

    BibCard [file] [def | scr | pub <name>]

        FILE              - Name of bib file.

        DEF or DEFSCREEN  - Switch to select the default public screen.

        SCR or CUSTSCREEN - Switch to select a custom screen.

        PUB or PUBSCREEN  - Name of the public screen to open on.
@endnode

@node "Workbench" "Workbench Usage"
The ToolTypes are:

        FILE=<file>  - Name of bib file.

        SCREEN=<def|scr|pub<=name>>

                 def - Select the default public screen.

                 scr - Select a custom screen.

                 pub - Name of the public screen to open on.



The screen option need some more explaining. To open BibCard on a public
screen set the ToolType according to this:

        SCREEN=pub=PubScreenName

Where PubScreenName is the name of the publc screen.
@endnode

@node "Limitations" "Limitations"
Maximum bib files open           -  Unlimited (memory is limit) Maximum
characters in a field    -  2500 Maximum characters in Key field  -    64
@endnode

@node "Menu" "Menu Items"
Read @{"this" link "Overview" 0} for an overview about the main BibCard window and fields.

There are six menu's which are explained below.

  Project
  -------
    @{"New           " link "InOut" 0} - Opens a new bibcard window.
    @{"Open          " link "InOut" 0} - Load a bib file.
    @{"Merge         " link "InOut" 0} - Combines two bib files.
    @{"Save          " link "InOut" 0} - Save a bib file.
    @{"Save As       " link "InOut" 0} - Save a bib file specifying a new name.
    @{"Save Selection" link "InOut" 0} - Save only the selected items.
    @{"Iconfy        " link "Iconfy" 0} - Iconfy program on Workbench.
    @{"DropBox       " link "Iconfy" 0} - Create a DropBox on workbench.
    @{"Preferences   " link "Prefs" 0} - To set some preferences.
    @{"About         " link "About" 0} - Tells it all.
    @{"Quit          " link "Quit" 0} - Quit BibCard.

  Edit
  ----
    Add            - Add a new bib item at the end of the list.
    Duplicate      - Duplicate the current item without the Cite Key.
    Delete         - Delete the current item.
    Delete Marked  - Delete the marked items.
    @{"Annotation    " link "Annotation" 0}     - Edit the annotation for the current item.
    Preamble       - Edit the preamble for the current file.
    @{"Abbrevations  " link "Abbrev" 0}   - Edit the Abbrevations for the current file
    @{"Unknown Fields" link "Unknown" 0} - Edit unknown fields for the current item.
    Cut            - Removes the current item and store's it in its
                     internal buffer.
    Copy           - Copy the current item to the internal buffer.
    Paste          - Inserts the internal buffer after the current item.

  @{"Entry" link "Entries" 0}
  -----
    Here you can select the entry type for the current item.

  View
  ----
    Next   - Show next item.
    Prev   - Show previous item.
    First  - Go to first item.
    Last   - Go to last item.

  @{"Cite" link "CiteWindow" 0}
  ----
    List Cites - Show a ListView with all the Cite Keys.

  @{"Find" link "FindWindow" 0}
  ----
    Find      - Find an item witch matches some criteria.
    Find Next - Find the next item that matches the above.
    Find Prev - Find the previous item that matches the above.
@endnode

@node "InOut" "Saving and Loading"
The <New> option opens a @{"Bib Window" link "Overview" 0}. This window has the default name
`bibcard-<n>.bib' where <n> is a sequential number.

When selecting <Open...> the selected bib file is loaded into the current
window.

The <Merge...> option appends the selected file to the one in memory.
Duplicated CiteKeys will be loaded.

When you select <Save> that name will be used to store the bib file. There
will be NO WARNING if that file already exist so the file will be overwritten.
If the CiteKey field is empty you will be notified about it. It is not
possible to save a bib file with empty CiteKeys.

With the <Save Selection> option only those item that are selected in the
@{"Cite Window" link "CiteWindow" 0} or are selected by the @{"Find option" link "FindWindow" 0} are saved.

BibCard also supports the creation of an icon when a bibfile is saved. This
option can be selected in the @{"Preference Window" link "Prefs" 0}.

Because the window is an @{"AppWindow" link "Overview" 22} a bib file can also be loaded by dragging a
bib file icon into the window and than releasing it.
@endnode

@node "Quit" "Quit          "
When you quit BibCard it checks first of the bibfiles in memory are changed.
For every bibfile changed it asks of you want to [Save it], [Don't save] but
continue or [Cancel] the operation.
@endnode

@node "Overview" "Overview Main Window and Fields"
 The window adapts itself to the number of fields for the different entries,
and it will grow or shrink accordingly. (This behaviour can be changed in the
@{"preferences" link "Prefs" 0}.) Despite that not all the entries share the same fields you can
fill in every field for every entry, by changing the entry type to a type that
supports the field and then switch back to the original field. Although you
can not see the field it will be saved with the entry.

The @{"CiteKey" link "Fields" 0} field has a maxmum of 64 characters, all the other fields have a
maximum of 2500 characters.

For every entry there are required and optional @{"fields" link "Fields" 0}. The optional fields
are not required by BibCard, but are required for BiBTeX to work. BiBTeX will
warn you when you forgot the required fields. The optional fields are only
used by BiBTeX if they have a value.

The only field that has to be filled in for BibCard is the CiteKey field.

The window title shows the window number, the number of the current entry, the
total entries, the name of the bib file and an asterisk '*' if that item is
marked. It can be marked by pressing the '*' key, by the @{"Find" link "FindWindow" 0} option or when
the @{"Cite" link "CiteWindow" 0} window is open and selecting an entry there.

This window is also an AppWindow. This means that when you drop an icon on
this window, the associated file will be loaded. This will only work if
BibCard is opened on the Workbench screen. When more icons are multiple
selected and dragged into the window the first icon get's loaded into this
window and for the other icons a new window is created.
@endnode

@node "Iconfy" "Iconfy and DropBox"
 When the iconfy option is selected, BibCard closes all windows and creates an
AppIcon on the Workbench. All the memory that was taken by the windows is
freed. When the AppIcon is double clicked BibCard open all its windows again.

When the DropBox menu is selected BibCard creates an AppIcon on the Workbench.
The DropBox can be used to add bib files to BibCard. When an icon is dragged
on top off the DropBox, BibCard open a new window and load the file. This also
workes for multiple selected icons.

Double clicking on the DropBox makes the screen where BibCard resides the
frontmost screen.
@endnode

@node "CiteWindow" "Cite Window"
 When the Cite Window is opened you get a list of all the CiteKeys in the bib
file. When an entry is selected the Bib Window is updated, when you change the
entry in the Bib Window in any way, the selection in the Cite Window will not
change, except for the CiteKey.

The fields that are marked by the @{"Find" link "FindWindow" 0} option are highlighted. That way you
get a quick overview about the bib items that are matched.


With the Cycle Gadget you can select the fields that are shown in the
ListView. There are 27 different fields so be patient when you want a
particular field in the ListView. (CycleToMenu is recommended.)

You can use the 'c' or 'C' key to cycle through the Fields.

You can also sort the bibtex file on any of the fields. If the Cycle gadget is
set on the Author field and then select the Sort gadget the database will be
selected on the Author field.

The sorting will be from 'a' to 'z' and is case insensitive. Select the Rev
CheckBox for sorting in the reversed order.

The sorting is done with the Stricmp() function from utility.library so when
you have the locale.library installed it will use language specific code.


Highlighted items can be saved when the <@{"Save Selection" link "InOut" 0}> option is selected.
@endnode

@node "FindWindow" "Find Window"
 In the Find window you can enter a search expression. Every bib entry that
matches the search criterium get marked when you click the [FIND] button. An
'*' in the window's title bar informs you that the item is selected.

With the [NEXT] button you can display every next marked item in the list.
With the [PREV] button you can display every previous marked item in the
list.

The [UNTAG] button in the Find window clears all marked items.

By selecting the CheckBoxes, the checked fields are searched for the given
search expression. The state of the CheckBoxes will be remembered between
different calls.

For now it is not possible to edit the bib file while the Find window is open.
This will be changed in the future.

With the menu items <Find Next> and <Find Prev> you can go from marked item to
marked item and also be able to edit the items.

Items that are selected are highlighted in the @{"Cite Window" link "CiteWindow" 0}.

Items selected by the find option are saved when the <@{"Save Selection" link "InOut" 0}> option
is selected.


The following wildcards can be used to specify a pattern:

            Pattern Matches
            ------- --------
            ?       any single character
            c*      zero or more occurrences of character c
            c+      one or more occurrences of character c
            \\?      a question mark (?)
            \\*      an asterisk (*)
            \\+      a plus sign (+)

@endnode

@node "Annotation" "Annotation Window"
 For every BibFile opened there can be one Annotation Window open. You will
get a TextField gadget where you can enter multiple lines. There is no
filtering in the characters you enter. So if you enter three line feeds, there
will also three line feeds saved in the *.bib file.

There is no maximum of the number of characters you can enter in BibCard but
BiBTeX can have a maximum size for the annotation field.

Every bib item has his own Annotation field.
@endnode

@node "Abbrev" "Abbrevation Window"
 The abbrevations could be edited here. See the LaTeX manual for the use of
abbrevations. The entries should be in the form:

    jb = "Journal of Biology"

Thus: the abbrevation, a '=' character and then the full name surrounded by
double quotes.

With the [New] button you add an item to the list and with the [Delete] button
you can remove an item from the list. The abbrevations appear in the bibfile
as string entries, one string for each abbrevation.
@endnode

@node "Unknown" "Unknown Fields Window"
 Every field that is unknown for BibCard is stored and saved. When you want to
edit these fields you must use the Unknown Fields Window. With the [New]
button you add an item to the list and with the [Delete] button you can remove
an item from the list. The [Ok] button transfers everything to the current
BibItem while the [Cancel] button leaves the BibItem unchanged.

The fields have the following format:

    remark = "This is a remark."
@endnode

@node "Prefs" "Preferences"

 * Field delimiters:

    The field delimiters can be set here. When saving a bib file the
    field strings will be surrounded with a pair of braces {} or a pair
    of double quotes "".

    When you have a " in your bib entries, you must set the delimiters to
    braces because when reading the bib file all entries after the "
    will not be read in.

    Default is " (double quotes)


 * Fixed window size:

    When this is set, the window size will not change between the
    different entry types. This will speed up the change between
    different entries.

    Default is off.


 * Save icon:

   When this option is selected, an icon will be saved with each bibfile.


 * Font:

   The font for a custom screen can here be selected. All windows are
   font sensitive, only when very large font sizes are being used some
   cosmetic problems could occur.


 * Screen type:

    The screen type tells where BibCard will open its window. There are
    three possibilities:

        Default - Open on the default public screen.

        Custom  - Open a public screen for itself.

        Public  - Open on a named existing public screen

    When a custom screen is selected, a screen mode can be chosen with
    the ListView Button gadget next to the Screen Mode text field. For
    this option version 38 of the asl.library is required.

    When the last option is chosen, the name of the pubplic screen where
    BibCard must open can be entered in the string gadget.

    Default for screen type is default public screen and for the custom
    screen `PAL:High Res' or `NTSC:High Res' depending on the default
    frequency.


With [Save] the setting will be saved in the current directory in the file
`BibCard.prefs'. The [Use] button will use the settings without saving them.

When BibCard opens it looks first for the preference file in the current
directory (where BibCard is started from) and then in the PROGDIR: (where
BibCard resides).
@endnode

@node "Help" "Help options"
 Pressing Help in the main window gives some help about Help.

When the Help key is pressed inside a string gadget you get some information
explaining the use of the @{"field" link "Fields" 0}.

When selecting an entry type under the Entry menu and then pressing the Help
key without releasing the mouse button gives also some information about the
@{"entry" link "Entries" 0} type.

The Find Window gives also some help about the @{"wildcards" link "FindWindow" 25} that can be used.

The Abbrevation Window gives help about the @{"format" link "Abbrev" 0} of an abbrevation.

The Unknown Fields Window gives help about the @{"format" link "Unknown" 0} of an unknown field.
@endnode

@node "Future" "Future of BibCard"
There are still things to do, but this version is usable for the average
BiBTeX person. Things on the wish list are:

 - Locale support. (is that realy needed?)

 - Set some more preferences (ideas?).

 - ARexx port.

I hope these are implemented for v1.0.
@endnode

